paragraphs.text: Get over yourself. Stop worrying. And do something useful.

paragraphs.name: c31a
paragraphs.text: Checking is a habit that you can never fully eliminate. I still follow the NBA because I like it. Pick only one or two ‘checking’ vices you actually like. Eliminate the rest. You’re not missing anything anyway.

paragraphs.name: a76b
paragraphs.text: What did you write down while you’re reading this article?

paragraphs.name: 3ae0
paragraphs.text: Did I change it? Nope. I always tried to escape my issues. Escaping problems gives you some stamina to face your shitty life again. But you and I both know that problems never go away until you grab them by the root and extinguish them.
I don’t know. Doesn’t matter, really. What matters is this: If you keep saying yes, you’re living someone else’s life.

paragraphs.text: Okay I have one thing that it keeps beeping here inside when I hear rules. Having rules and/or adding more rules to your life besides all that you are living with, makes you more like a robot. You are very very far from that, but the fact is fact. paragraphs.text: Hey Darius. Wasn’t it you publishing a post on how to skim through the context of self-teaching guides in almost no time? I might be exaggerating a bit, but by dropping the essay style in favour of lists of does and don’ts you subject your (recent) posts to the very same technique applied by your readers. Loosing readers will then be the next step. Subjective, I know, but it is the way it goes for me.

7bbcff963876.title: I notice a lot of fake vetting questions in myself and in others in order to convince ourselves…

paragraphs.name: 8b25
paragraphs.text: I notice a lot of fake vetting questions in myself and in others in order to convince ourselves this person can’t have anything useful to offer in terms of advice and to trust ourselves. An example of a fake vetting question would be if someone was trying to help my alignment in yoga and I ask “so, can you do a handstand split?” And then decide they can’t help my alignment.
